	<p class="cs709C557D"><span class="cs8498B7A6">WEST VIRGINIA LEGISLATURE</span></p><p class="cs1CE9D70E"><span class="csB0C9F1E0">2026 </span><span class="csC2FEE544">REGULAR SESSION</span></p><p class="cs709C557D"><span class="csC2FEE544">Introduced</span></p><p class="cs3E63B65"><span class="cs8498B7A6">Senate Bill 708</span></p><p class="csFF933113"><span class="csADC6E5DB">By Senators Woodrum and Hart</span></p><p class="cs8BEF69CE"><span class="cs7B75DFFE">[Introduced February 2, 2026; referred<br/>to the Committee on Natural Resources; and then to the Committee on the Judiciary]</span></p><p class="cs29F66C3F"><span class="csEF05ACC">A BILL to amend the Code of West Virginia, 1931, as amended, by adding a new article, designated &sect;17-4B-1, &sect;17-4B-2, &sect;17-4B-3, &sect;17-4B-4, &sect;17-4B-5, &sect;17-4B-6, &sect;17-4B-7, &sect;17-4B-8, &sect;17-4B-9, &sect;17-4B-10, &sect;17-4B-11, &sect;17-4B-12, &sect;17-4B-13, and &sect;17-4B-14, relating to public river access and public safety in connection with bridge projects and hazardous river segments; creating a short title; providing legislative findings and purpose; providing definitions; clarifying how to evaluate river access during bridge projects; establishing when to undertake public access improvements; prohibiting eminent domain; requiring safety and design standards; prioritizing public safety; authorizing informational signage in certain situations; clarifying liability; authorizing inter-agency coordination; providing grant and funding authority; and providing legislative review. &nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p><p class="cs63FD752D"><span class="cs93AB6E8B">Be it enacted by the Legislature of West Virginia:</span></p><p class="cs63FD752D"><span class="cs93AB6E8B">&nbsp;</span></p><h2 class="cs89687900">
		<span class="cs456817A0">ARTICLE 4B. West Virginia River Access and Bridge Modernization Act.</span></h2>
	<h4 class="cs89687900">
		<span class="csF3C8A5A3">&sect;17-4B-1. Short title.</span></h4>
	<p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">This article shall be known and may be cited as the &quot;West Virginia River Access and Bridge Modernization Act.&quot;</span></p><p class="cs63FD752D"><span class="cs93AB6E8B">&nbsp;</span></p><h4 class="cs89687900">
		<span class="csF3C8A5A3">&sect;17-4B-2. Legislative findings and purpose.</span></h4>
	<p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">The Legislature finds that:</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(1) Bridges crossing navigable waterways are frequently used by the public for lawful recreational activities, including fishing, boating, and paddling;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(2) Unmanaged or informal river access increases risks to public safety, emergency response personnel, and the traveling public, and may result in unnecessary environmental degradation;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(3) Inadequate or unsafe ingress and egress from navigable waterways contributes to emergency rescues, injuries, and fatalities, including incidents requiring response by fire departments, emergency medical services, law enforcement, and search-and-rescue personnel;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(4) The provision of controlled and properly designed river access can reduce the frequency, complexity, and danger of rescue operations and improve overall public safety; and</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(5) It is the intent of the Legislature to encourage safe, voluntary, and fiscally responsible public river access without the use of eminent domain, without interference with private property rights, and without expanding the authority of the Division of Highways beyond that expressly provided by this article.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="csEF05ACC">&nbsp;</span></p><h4 class="cs89687900">
		<span class="csF3C8A5A3">&sect;17-4B-3. Definitions.</span></h4>
	<p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">For purposes of this article:</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">&quot;Division&quot; means the West Virginia Division of Highways.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">&quot;Navigable waterway&quot; means a river or stream capable of recreational navigation for a substantial portion of the year.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">&quot;Public river access facility&quot; means a designed and managed location providing ingress to and egress from a navigable waterway, including pull-offs, user-specific parking or staging areas, paths, under-bridge access areas, or related orientation features.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">&quot;Substantial bridge project&quot; means the construction, replacement, or rehabilitation of a bridge crossing a navigable waterway.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="csEF05ACC">&nbsp;</span></p><h4 class="cs89687900">
		<span class="csF3C8A5A3">&sect;17-4B-4. Evaluation of river access during bridge projects.</span></h4>
	<p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(a) When undertaking a substantial bridge project over a navigable waterway, the division shall evaluate whether a public river access facility may be safely and practicably provided.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(b) Nothing in this section shall be construed to require construction of a public river access facility where site conditions, safety concerns, environmental constraints, funding limitations, or right-of-way considerations make such construction impracticable.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="csEF05ACC">&nbsp;</span></p><h4 class="cs89687900">
		<span class="csF3C8A5A3">&sect;17-4B-5. Authority to construct public river access facilities.</span></h4>
	<p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(a) The division may design, construct, improve, or maintain public river access facilities when the division determines that such access:</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(1) Can be accommodated safely;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(2) Does not interfere with traffic or transportation operations; and</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(3) Improves public safety or resource protection, including mitigation of hazardous river conditions, unsafe ingress or egress, or conditions contributing to emergency response or rescue incidents.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(b) The division may undertake public river access improvements independent of a bridge project when necessary to address documented public safety concerns.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(c) Notwithstanding the absence of a bridge construction, replacement, or rehabilitation project, the division may design and construct limited public river access facilities, including user-specific parking or staging areas, when necessary to mitigate unsafe ingress or egress conditions or to reduce the likelihood or severity of emergency response or rescue operations.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(d) Facilities constructed pursuant to subsection (c) shall be limited in size and scope to what is reasonably necessary to achieve public safety objectives.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="csEF05ACC">&nbsp;</span></p><h4 class="cs89687900">
		<span class="csF3C8A5A3">&sect;17-4B-6. Prohibition on eminent domain; voluntary acquisition permitted for safety purposes.</span></h4>
	<p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(a) The division may not exercise eminent domain to acquire property for the purpose of creating or expanding a public river access facility or related parking or staging area under this article.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(b) Notwithstanding subsection (a), the division may acquire real property or interests therein from willing sellers, by purchase, donation, or voluntary easement, for the limited purpose of improving public safety through safe ingress or egress, including user-specific parking or staging areas.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(c) Any acquisition under this section shall:</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(1) Be voluntary and without the use or threat of eminent domain;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(2) Be limited in size and scope to what is reasonably necessary to achieve public safety or rescue-mitigation objectives; and</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(3) Not interfere with agricultural operations, timber operations, fencing, gates, or other lawful working-land uses unless expressly agreed to by the property owner.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(d) Nothing in this section shall be construed to require the division to acquire property.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="csEF05ACC">&nbsp;</span></p><h4 class="cs89687900">
		<span class="csF3C8A5A3">&sect;17-4B-7. Safety and design standards.</span></h4>
	<p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(a) Public river access facilities constructed under this article shall incorporate reasonable safety features appropriate to site conditions.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(b) The division may utilize existing engineering, transportation, or recreational-access design standards and is not required to promulgate new rules solely to implement this article.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="csEF05ACC">&nbsp;</span></p><h4 class="cs89687900">
		<span class="csF3C8A5A3">&sect;17-4B-8. Public safety and rescue-mitigation prioritization.</span></h4>
	<p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(a) In carrying out the authority granted under this article, the division shall prioritize the evaluation and development of public river access facilities at locations where improved access would reasonably:</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(1) Reduce the likelihood, frequency, or severity of emergency response or rescue operations involving fire departments, emergency medical services, law enforcement, or search-and-rescue personnel;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(2) Address hazardous or advanced-difficulty river segments where the absence of safe ingress or egress increases rescue risk;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(3) Mitigate unsafe, impracticable, or hazardous ingress or egress conditions, including steep climbs, extended carries, difficult terrain, or conflicts with vehicular traffic; or</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(4) Improve responder access to incident locations for emergency response purposes.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(b) In applying the prioritization set forth in this section, the division may consider, as available and appropriate:</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(1) Documented emergency response or rescue activity;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(2) Known or documented patterns of public use;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(3) Consultation with fire departments, emergency medical services, law enforcement, search-and-rescue personnel, or other local officials; and</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(4) Site conditions affecting public safety.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(c) Nothing in this section shall be construed to:</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(1) Require the construction of a public river access facility at any specific location;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(2) Create a duty to provide access at all hazardous river segments; or</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(3) Expand the liability of the division beyond that imposed by general law.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="csEF05ACC">&nbsp;</span></p><h4 class="cs89687900">
		<span class="csF3C8A5A3">&sect;17-4B-9. Informational signage; limitation of duty and liability.</span></h4>
	<p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(a) The division may install informational signage when it determines such signage would reasonably improve public safety or user orientation.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(b) Informational signage may include:</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(1) Identification of the bridge, access point, or river segment;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(2) Location-reference information for user orientation;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(3) Approximate distance or estimated travel time to the next access point;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(4) General, non-technical descriptions of river character;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(5) General water-safety advisories, including personal flotation device recommendations;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(6) Advisories that cellular telephone service may be limited or unavailable and that rescue response may be delayed; or</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(7) Advisories encouraging users to exercise personal responsibility and possess the skills, equipment, and group capacity reasonably necessary for self-rescue.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(c) Signage may be located on or beneath bridges, at access facilities, or at other appropriate locations.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(d) In developing signage, the division may rely upon existing standards or best practices used by transportation, natural resource, or land-management agencies.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(e) Nothing in this section shall be construed to:</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(1) Require signage installation or maintenance on a fixed schedule;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(2) Require continued presence or accuracy of signage following flooding, erosion, or channel changes;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(3) Create a representation or warranty regarding river conditions or hazards;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(4) Require identification of every potential hazard; or</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(5) Expand the liability or legal duty of the division beyond that imposed by general law.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="csEF05ACC">&nbsp;</span></p><h4 class="cs89687900">
		<span class="csF3C8A5A3">&sect;17-4B-10. Limitation of liability.</span></h4>
	<p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">Nothing in this article shall be construed to create a duty beyond that imposed by general law or to expand the liability of the Division for injuries occurring at or near a public river access facility.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="csEF05ACC">&nbsp;</span></p><h4 class="cs89687900">
		<span class="csF3C8A5A3">&sect;17-4B-11. Interagency coordination.</span></h4>
	<p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">The division may coordinate and enter into cooperative agreements with state, federal, regional, or local governmental agencies or political subdivisions for purposes authorized by this article.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="csEF05ACC">&nbsp;</span></p><h4 class="cs89687900">
		<span class="csF3C8A5A3">&sect;17-4B-12. Grant and funding authority &mdash; governmental sources.</span></h4>
	<p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">The division may apply for, accept, and expend state or federal grants, mitigation funds, enhancement funds, or other public monies to support public river access facilities authorized by this article.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="csEF05ACC">&nbsp;</span></p><h4 class="cs89687900">
		<span class="csF3C8A5A3">&sect;17-4B-13. Grant and funding authority &mdash; non-governmental sources.</span></h4>
	<p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(a) The division may accept grants, donations, or financial assistance from non-governmental sources for purposes authorized by this article.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(b) Such acceptance shall not confer ownership, control, naming rights, or management authority, expand acquisition authority, or impose conditions inconsistent with this article.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(c) Public or grant funds may be used to support voluntary property acquisition authorized under &sect;17-4B-6 of this article.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="csEF05ACC">&nbsp;</span></p><h4 class="cs89687900">
		<span class="csF3C8A5A3">&sect;17-4B-14. Legislative review.</span></h4>
	<p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">Within five years of enactment, the division shall report to the Joint Committee on Government and Finance regarding implementation, safety outcomes, and funding sources utilized under this article.</span></p><p class="cs637BA255"><span class="cs7FA9C667">&nbsp;</span></p><p class="cs637BA255"><span class="cs7FA9C667">NOTE: The purpose of this bill is to encourage safe, voluntary, and fiscally responsible public river access without the use of eminent domain, without interference with private property rights, and without expanding the authority of the Division of Highways beyond that expressly provided by this article.</span></p><p class="cs637BA255"><span class="cs7FA9C667">Strike-throughs indicate language that would be stricken from a heading or the present law and underscoring indicates new language that would be added.</span></p>


